data.name: Example Annotation Project
data.description:
This annotation project serves serves as an example project to showcase the Whombat annotation tool. It features short audio clips showcasing the diverse vocalizations of bats from Costa Rica. These clips are derived from the "Example Xenocanto" dataset, also available within Whombat example data.

To generate annotation tasks, 1-second clips were extracted from the source recordings. This 1-second duration was chosen to standardize the length of each annotation task, making the annotation process more manageable, especially when dealing with very long recordings. For longer recordings, the audio was segmented into multiple 1-second clips, and each clip was converted into an individual annotation task to ensure that the full content of the recording is covered.

The primary annotation task involves identifying and marking all instances of bat echolocation calls within each audio clip. Annotators used bounding boxes to precisely define the spectro-temporal boundaries of these calls.

All annotations were made by Santiago Martínez Balvanera
data.instructions:
Carefully listen to the 1-second audio clip and visually inspect the spectrogram. Use the playback controls and zoom function in Whombat to examine the clip in detail.

Locate all discernible bat echolocation calls within the clip. Use the PCEN denoising function to enhance the contrast between calls and background noise. Adjust the window size (smaller windows like 1ms with high overlap of 80% are recommended for better temporal resolution) if needed. In challenging cases, try turning PCEN off.

Annotate each echolocation call with a bounding box.  Ensure the bounding box is as tight as possible, encompassing the entire call while minimizing the inclusion of background noise.  Zoom in as needed to accurately place the box, ensuring the start and end of the call touch the edges. Include all spectrogram bins that are significantly higher than the base noise level within the bounding box.

If a call has multiple harmonic components, annotate only the main component. The main harmonic is usually the component with the highest amplitude (brightest in the spectrogram). Maintain consistency in annotating the same harmonic component throughout the project, even if its amplitude varies slightly in some calls. Refer to scientific publications or other recordings of the same species to confirm the main harmonic if you are unsure.

Identify the species of the bat emitting the call whenever possible. This information is available in the recording metadata. The targeted individual is typically the most prominent in the recording and often the only one recorded. If the species of the call cannot be identified with certainty, use the generic tag "order:Chiroptera". Ignore any sounds that do not resemble bat echolocation calls.

If a call is cut off by the clip boundaries, annotate the visible portion. Do not attempt to extrapolate or guess the missing part. Add the tag "call_quality:truncated" to these annotations.

Take your time and annotate meticulously. If you encounter any uncertainties while annotating, don't hesitate to add notes to the annotation, create an issue to flag the problem or seek clarification from the project administrators. Before submitting your work, zoom out to view the entire spectrogram and carefully scan the recording to ensure all echolocation calls have been annotated and no calls have been missed.
